# Tailwind CSS + Next.js

## Component creation

When building UI, analyze requirements first, then:

- Reuse or extend primitives in `components/ui/` before creating one-offs
- Use `cn()` from `@/lib/cn` to merge Tailwind classes
- Define explicit TypeScript types for props; avoid `any`, prefer `unknown` with guards
- Include responsive variants (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`) and accessible markup (labels, focus, ARIA)
- Handle loading, error, and empty states for data-driven UI
- Prefer Server Components; add `'use client'` only for interactivity, hooks, or browser APIs

## Next.js (App Router)

- Use `app/` routes with bracket segments for dynamic params (e.g. `app/shop/[slug]/page.tsx`)
- Validate and sanitize route params before use
- Fetch in Server Components with async components; use `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, and `not-found.tsx`
- Use `next/image` with `sizes`, `priority` when above the fold, and explicit dimensions
- Colocate route UI under `app/`; shared UI under `components/`

## TypeScript

- `strict: true` is required; type parameters, returns, and complex props explicitly
- Use `type` for unions and variant maps; use `interface` only when extension is needed
- Prefer discriminated unions over ambiguous unions

## Tailwind CSS v4

- Style with utility classes; avoid custom CSS unless tokens, keyframes, or global base styles
- Define design tokens in `app/globals.css` via `@theme inline` (colors, fonts, animations)
- Reference tokens as utilities (e.g. `text-ink`, `bg-accent`, `font-display`)
- Keep class order consistent: layout → spacing → typography → color → border → effects → states
- Use project animations (`animate-fade-up`, `animate-fade-in`) for motion instead of ad-hoc CSS

## Project structure

- `components/` — presentational and feature components
- `components/ui/` — reusable primitives (Button, Card, Input, etc.)
- `lib/` — utilities, types, data helpers
- `app/` — routes, layouts, global styles

## Quality

- Run `npm run lint` before committing; fix ESLint issues
- Use Conventional Commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`)
- Keep changes small and focused; add tests for non-trivial logic when appropriate
